<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><title>Blog</title><link href="//tdi.github.io/" rel="alternate"></link><link href="//tdi.github.io/feeds/latex.atom.xml" rel="self"></link><id>//tdi.github.io/</id><updated>2013-01-30T12:00:39+01:00</updated><entry><title>Text above arrows in LaTeX</title><link href="//tdi.github.io/2013/01/30/text-above-arrows-in-latex/" rel="alternate"></link><published>2013-01-30T12:00:39+01:00</published><author><name>Dariusz Dwornikowski</name></author><id>tag:tdi.github.io,2013-01-30:2013/01/30/text-above-arrows-in-latex/</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;Sometimes you need to place text above arrows. Let's say you need to write transitions for a labelled transition system. In fact in LaTeX this is not so obvious, especially if you want to have text above and under the arrow. I know of two easy ways to do it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="sb"&gt;$$&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt; E &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;\xrightarrow&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;\alpha&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;} F &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;$$&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The second method.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="sb"&gt;$$&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;\mathop&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;\longrightarrow&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;}^_{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;\alpha&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;} &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;$$&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
</summary><category term="latex"></category></entry></feed>